ANTHRAX - ARGENTINA (02): (BUENOS AIRES) CATTLE
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 4 Jul 2019
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


Rural anthrax (3 outbreaks) in the Province of Buenos Aires
----------------------------------------------------------
In the partido (county) of Carlos Casares there were 2 outbreaks in February and March 2019:
(1) The 1st was at an inn ("Tambo") where 7 Holland Argentino cows in a dairy herd died; they were diagnosed clinically and microbiologically confirmed by the isolation of _Bacillus anthracis_. The affected herd was partially vaccinated, and it is possible that the affected animals had not been vaccinated. The carcasses were soaked with 5% formalin and buried. The outbreak was reported to the provincial and national sanitary control agencies.

(2) The 2nd outbreak, also in Carlos Casares, was in a breeding herd neighbouring the previous herd, and where 2 cattle died from the same cause [and presumably similarly confirmed]. [The herd] was only partially vaccinated. It is in a high-risk zone for flooding, close to the Rio Salado, and ecologically suitable [high calcium levels, high pH] for the survival and maintenance of _B. anthracis_ spores.

(3) The 3rd outbreak occurred in the county of Olavarria, Recalde municipality, in May 2019. This is also in a low-lying area and a short distance from a local epidemic involving 8 outbreaks [4 Mar 2013 Anthrax - Argentina (03): (BA) bovine, human 20130304.1570248; starting in late February 2013]. The estancia [small farm] is dedicated to breeding cattle. Normally the cattle are well vaccinated, but there is a suspicion that it might have been incomplete, with a single death. The carcass was disposed of using the traditional "tapado controlado" method [see 13 Mar 2018 Anthrax, bovine - Argentina (02): (BS) alternative disposal of carcasses 20180313.5684083]. There were no human cases, and the outbreak was reported to the provincial and national sanitary control agencies.

